<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Phyllis W. Jordan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 PSYCHO THRILLER: Three decades ago his book "Psycho" became a blood-tingling 
movie, making his twisted killer, Norman Bates, a household name. Author Robert 
Bloch had planned to spend Halloween in Ventura, signing copies of the 35th 
anniversary edition of the book. . . . Sadly, Bloch died in September. But the 
Phantom Bookshop on Main Street is planning a "posthumous book signing" this 
afternoon to sell 75 copies he autographed before his death. 
</P>
<P>
 NO SUGAR TONIGHT: Trick-or-treating can be tough if you can't eat sweets. 
That's why Ventura County Medical Center sponsored a camp for diabetic children 
this weekend, handing out sugarless treats, fruit and other suitable snacks. . 
. . The youngsters also competed in a costume contest and mummy wrap. . . . 
Diabetes strikes more than 50,000 people in Ventura County, hitting Latinos 
particularly hard. Local eye doctors have banded together to give free exams 
for diabetics, who risk blindness if untreated. (B1) 
</P>
<P>
 MONEY TREE: As if the Civic Arts Plaza wasn't enough to put Thousand Oaks on 
the map, the city has installed the first of several signs designed to let 
motorists know they've arrived. . . . The four-foot, concrete-and-brass sign on 
Olsen Road marks the border with Simi Valley. Denise Filz, who designed the 
gateway-to-the-city markers, calls the textured oak tree "something truly 
unique, with a natural feeling." Critics call it expensive, at $5,000 a sign. 
</P>
<P>
 FINAL SALUTE: It lost its county funding two years ago. Now the Ventura County 
Commission for Women could be losing its annual awards contest. . . . After 
receiving only 17 nominees for all 12 Salute to Women categories, commission 
members decided to cancel this fall's banquet. They'll give one final round of 
awards next spring, then retire the contest after 12 years. "It's kind of sad, 
isn't it?" commissioner Loma Siegel said, adding that other groups have picked 
up the slack in recognizing women's achievements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
