<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; NEW YORK; CBS UNDER FIRE FOR ASTEROIDS TV HOAX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A fictional news broadcast showing gigantic asteroids crash-landing on Earth 
took Americans by surprise, with TV viewers jamming CBS switchboards to find 
out if their world was coming to an end. Titled "Without Warning," the program 
attributed fictional reports of worldwide disaster to news outlets such as 
Reuters and The Associated Press and showed scenes of panic and death on the 
ground, massive tie-ups in the skies above the United States and the collapse 
of the world's stock markets. The broadcast was reminiscent of Orson Welles' 
famous 1938 radio dramatization of H.G. Wells' "War of the Worlds" 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA103194-0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 094022 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
October 31, 1994, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 15; Column 1; National Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1089 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEROT VOTERS LEANING TO THE RIGHT IN '94; POLITICS: HIS SUPPORTERS ARE EXPECTED 
TO PLAY A CRUCIAL ROLE IN THE MIDTERM ELECTIONS. AND THE DEMOCRATS ARE NOT TOO 
HAPPY ABOUT IT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THOMAS B. ROSENSTIEL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In theory, they are the pivotal part of the American electorate -- the 
critical middle that wishes a pox on all houses of government. And in next 
week's elections, they could tip whether Congress goes Republican or 
Democratic, decide dozens of individual races and forge the direction of 
government for two years. 
</P>
<P>
 They are the Perot vote, that 20% of the electorate that helped Ross Perot 
mount the most successful independent presidential candidacy in 70 years. Now, 
two years later, what remains of his supporters and which way are they leaning? 
</P>
<P>
 The answer, Republicans gleefully speculate and Democrats fret, is they are 
going Republican on Nov. 8. 
</P>
<P>
 "They are the same-sized group (as two years ago), but different people -- and 
it looks pretty grim" for Democrats, said President Clinton's pollster, Stanley 
B. Greenberg. A study by Greenberg in July identified the 20 million Perot 
voters as "the pivotal force in American politics." 
</P>
<P>
 In 1992, "we wanted to make sure we were splitting the Perot vote in our local 
races," said Republican pollster Linda Divall. "This year we hope to get 60% of 
them." Others predicted that Republicans will get even more than that. 
</P>
<P>
 The Perot bloc appears to be tipping Senate races in Wyoming, Montana, 
Oklahoma, Michigan and Maine to the Republicans. They are also playing a 
crucial role in pulling voters away from House Speaker Thomas S. Foley 
(D-Wash.), who could become the first Speaker to lose a reelection bid in 130 
years. And the Perot bloc is hurting even moderate Democratic incumbents in 
dozens of other races, particularly in the West and the Northeast, where 
Perot's appeal is strongest. 
</P>
<P>
 Perot announced two weeks ago that he believes his supporters should back the 
Republican Party. But there are doubts about the power of that endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Perot factor is what I call 'ephemeral heresy,' " said Democratic 
pollster Peter Hart. "They left George Bush for Ross Perot in 1992, and they 
are returning to the Republican Party in 1994." 
</P>
<P>
 The shifting has occurred as fundamental changes have taken place in the core 
of Perot's support. In the last two years, the Texas billionaire has lost much 
of his appeal among independent middle-class and upper-middle-class 
suburbanites and women. They have been replaced by seething-mad blue-collar 
voters, predominantly men, whom pollsters used to call Ronald Reagan Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
 At the moment, Clinton has thoroughly antagonized these angry voters. "They 
are a 10 on the saliva test," said Republican pollster Frank Luntz, who was 
formerly Perot's pollster. "When you mention Washington, they practically spray 
you they get so agitated." 
</P>
<P>
 "Perot had two bases of support -- those who wanted to change government and 
those who wanted to torch it," said Democratic pollster Celinda Lake, who is 
closely studying the Perot phenomenon. "He kept the torchers; in fact, he got 
more of them, but he lost the changers." 
</P>
<P>
 "His middle-class supporters still like his message, but they have become sour 
about the messenger," Luntz said.  
</P>
<P>
 The shift has also raised doubts about the number of Perot supporters who will 
take the time to vote Nov. 8. An ever-larger percentage of the Perot bloc is 
made up of alienated voters who are less likely to turn out at the polls, 
especially in midterm elections, said Ed Sarpolus, a Michigan pollster who has 
watched the Perot vote in his state. 
</P>
<P>
 Luntz predicted that Perot voters will be 8% to 10% of the midterm electorate. 
Lake predicted that it could be as high as 16%. 
</P>
<P>
 Democrats also apparently have failed to capture another, potentially more 
promising group of voters -- those who gave their allegiance to Perot two years 
ago but have since turned away. They are considered more volatile than Perot 
devotees and could go for either party in November. 
</P>
<P>
 "The key for my party right now is to appeal to those people who have given up 
on Perot," Lake said. 
</P>
<P>
 Looking ahead to 1996, Perot's appeal among Republicans is a double-edged 
sword for the party. His support can be helpful but, if he runs again, he could 
siphon off even more Republican support than he did in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 "When we run three ways with Perot, Clinton goes ahead against Bob Dole," the 
Senate minority leader, Lake said. "Perot even makes it close for Clinton 
against Colin Powell," the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff who 
draws high marks in polls. 
</P>
<P>
 The Republican tendencies of Perot supporters also mean that Perot's 
endorsement of Republicans today means less than it once did. Most of his 
supporters would have voted Republican anyway. 
</P>
<P>
 There are even indications that many Perot supporters have stopped listening 
to him. A survey by the Times Mirror Center for The People & The Press last 
week found that only 30% of those who said they were Perot supporters even knew 
of Perot's recommendation to vote Republican, which he made several weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, the poll found that his endorsements apparently carry little sway 
with other voters. More of those polled said Perot's recommendation makes them 
"less inclined" to vote for Republicans than said it influenced them (7% 
compared with 3%). 
</P>
<P>
 There are some exceptions, however, where Perot supporters or endorsements may 
be swaying voters. 
</P>
<P>
 In Spokane, Wash., for instance, the local Perot organization, United We 
Stand, America, Inc. has developed credibility in the community and its strong 
anti-incumbent sentiments have hurt Foley greatly, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
 Perot also apparently has influence when he makes an exception to his general 
endorsement and backs individual Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
 In Perot's home state of Texas, he has endorsed Gov. Ann Richards over 
Republican George W. Bush. The endorsement could be worth three or four 
percentage points at the polls if Richards publicizes it, Democratic pollster 
Harrison Hickman contended. 
</P>
<P>
 In Colorado, Perot endorsed Democratic Gov. Roy Romer over former United We 
Stand member Bruce Benson, a Republican. The impact is difficult to assess in a 
race where Romer has built a sizable lead. 
</P>
<P>
 One final question about the Perot phenomenon of 1994 is about the same as it 
was two years ago. What does Perot want? 
</P>
<P>
 Both parties are unclear about his motives in supporting the Republican 
agenda. Democrats believe he is setting up the Republicans for a fall, sensing 
that little will change in two years. 
</P>
<P>
 But at least some Republicans are saying that they believe him. "The man can't 
be President and he probably knows it," Luntz said. "So I have to have some 
faith that his endorsement of Republicans is sincere." 
</P>
</TEXT>
