<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
October 31, 1994, Monday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 3; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
181 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY ALMANAC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In Irvine, anybody who fires up a leaf blower on a Sunday is violating city 
law. 
</P>
<P>
 While the use of leaf blowers is allowed Monday through Saturday until 5 p.m., 
the city has established rigorous rules of operation. 
</P>
<P>
 All leaf blowers used in the city must first be tested and approved by city 
officials and must bear a city approval label. Anyone who wants to use an 
approved leaf blower must complete a city training session. The operator must 
take the course every two years. 
</P>
<P>
 And before use, operators must check for wind direction, freshly washed cars, 
children or pets at play, and open doors and windows. Leaf blower debris must 
be cleared away within six hours. 
</P>
<P>
 Today 
</P>
<P>
 Ceramic artist Adrian Saxe will discuss his work at Rancho Santiago College. 
</P>
<P>
 The discussion take place at noon at the college's campus at 1530 W. 17th St. 
in Santa Ana. 
</P>
<P>
 It is part of the Art Forum series of lectures sponsored by the college. The 
lecture series has highlighted several artists and their creations. 
</P>
<P>
 The talk, which is free, will take place in Room C-104. 
</P>
<P>
 Information: (714) 564-5600. 
</P>
</TEXT>
